lead_paragraph: CROTHERS--Samuel H., 75, Tony Award-winning producer of a number of groundbreaking Broadway musicals and films, passed away quietly on Saturday, April 13, 2013 in his Boynton Beach, Florida home after a battle with Lymphoma. The son of Lucy Aurora (Tutunjian) Crothers and Samuel H. Crothers, Sam was a native of Newark, NJ. He served in the U.S. Navy as a medical corpsman, graduated from Rutgers University in 1962, and went on to work in a variety of jobs, including stints in the New York Times obituary department and at Palmes Del Mar Resort in Puerto Rico, before his love of theater led him to The Producer Circle Co. in 1975, where he became Managerial Partner. For years, Sam was known throughout the theatrical community as the backbone of the company, serving as the driving force for many of its innovative projects. His extensive list of Broadway credits includes the Tony Award-winning Sweeney Todd starring Angela Lansbury, La Cage aux Folles (both the original production and the 2004 revival), and The Will Rogers Follies - as well as his sentimental favorite, the musical Roza, starring Georgia Brown. His movie credits include Fort Apache The Bronx, The Boys from Brazil, The Shining, and the Academy Award-winning Chicago. "The Old Dog", as he cheerfully referred to himself, is forever immortalized by a caricature that hangs at Sardi's. Sam was a tremendously generous, loyal, and devoted friend and family man. He loved the beach and swimming in the ocean, and was an avid Winston Churchill scholar. Sam cherished his Armenian heritage and is survived by his brother, David Crothers; his sister, Diane Scholz; his aunt, Virginia Tutunjian, and a huge extended family of nephews, nieces, cousins, and good friends who he considered family. Many glasses of Johnnie Walker Red will surely be raised in his honor. Per his request, no services are planned
